Part I - San Francisco Ford GoBikes Analysis¶

by Emmanuel Owoka¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. This dataset includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.The Ford GoBike services is a bike sharing transportation provided by Ford that is easy to use, enjoyable and convenient. The dataset contains the 2019 for the month of February records which has 183,412 records and 16 features. I am going to be carrying out exploratory and explanatory data analysis on the dataset.

Observations from the dataset¶

Some quality and tidiness issues were observed in the dataset.

  • Wrong/incorrect datatypes: start_time and end_time datatypes should be converted to datetime datatypes. The user_type, member_gender and bike_share_for_all_trip should be converted to categorical datatypes. Bike_id, start_station_id, end_station_id should be converted to string datatype. Member_birth_year should be converted to int datatype.
  • minutes should be extracted from duraration and start_time variable should be splitted into hour of the day, day of the week and month of the year.
  • Member ages should be derived from member birth year

Data Cleaning¶

In [11]:
#make a copy of the original dataset
ford_bikes_clean = ford_bikes.copy()
In [12]:
#convert datatypes

#start time and end_time variables to datetime datatype
ford_bikes_clean['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(ford_bikes_clean['start_time'])
ford_bikes_clean['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(ford_bikes_clean['end_time'])

#user_type, member_gender, bike_share to categorical datatype
for col in ['member_gender', 'user_type', 'bike_share_for_all_trip']:
    ford_bikes_clean[col] = ford_bikes_clean[col].astype('category')
    
#bike_id, start_station_id, end_station_id to string datatype
for bse in ['bike_id', 'start_station_id', 'end_station_id']:
    ford_bikes_clean[bse] = ford_bikes_clean[bse].astype('object')
    
#member_birth_year to int
#drop rows with null values
ford_bikes_clean = ford_bikes_clean.dropna(subset = ['member_birth_year'])
ford_bikes_clean['member_birth_year'] = ford_bikes_clean['member_birth_year'].astype('int')

#extract minutes from duration and split the start_time variables into hour of the day, day of the week and month of the year
ford_bikes_clean['duration_minutes'] = ford_bikes_clean['duration_sec']/60

ford_bikes_clean['start_hour_num'] = ford_bikes_clean['start_time'].apply(lambda time: time.hour)
ford_bikes_clean['start_hour_name'] = 'morning'
ford_bikes_clean['start_hour_name'][(ford_bikes_clean['start_hour_num'] >=12) & (ford_bikes_clean['start_hour_num'] <= 17)] = 'afternoon'
ford_bikes_clean['start_hour_name'][(ford_bikes_clean['start_hour_num'] >=18) & (ford_bikes_clean['start_hour_num'] <= 23)] = 'night'


ford_bikes_clean['start_day_of_week'] = ford_bikes_clean.start_time.dt.strftime('%A')
ford_bikes_clean['start_month_name'] = ford_bikes_clean.start_time.dt.strftime('%b')

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, I am going to investigate distributions of individual variables. If I see unusual points or outliers, I would take a deeper look to clean things up and prepare to look at relationships between different variables.

I am going to be creating a list of user-defined functions

In [20]:
#user-defined function for countplots
def countplot(ford_bikes_clean, column, order = None, color=None):
    plt.figure(figsize=[9,8])
    sb.countplot(data = ford_bikes_clean, x=column, color = color, order=order);
    plt.title(f'''Distribution of trip count based on {column}'''.title(), fontsize=12, weight ='bold')
    plt.xlabel(column.title(),fontsize=10, weight='bold')
    plt.ylabel('Trip Count'.title(),fontsize=10,weight='bold')

Observation¶

From the above plot, subscribers go on trips more than customers. That means the bike services have more subscribers than customers, maybe the subscription price is reasonable enough and the customers might be tourists.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

It was quite interesting to see that Customers have longer trips than Subscribers. I was expecting the subscribers to have longer trips because of the fact that they are more than Customers.

Conclusions¶

In this exploratory data analysis, I investigated the ford GoBike services for February 2019. There was some cleaning and tidying of the data like correcting datatypes, splitting of variables, getting rid of outliersm etc. I investigated relationships between variables. Univariate, Bivariate and Multivariate explorations were used to investigate these relationships and some great insights were revealed. It was interesting to see that although there are more subscribers than customers, customer's trips durations are longer than that of subscribers. The older the age of a user, the lesser the trip. Most trips occur during the day and from Monday to friday than at night and on Saturdays and Sundays. There are many more relationships that revealed great insights in this analysis. Other relationships can be investigated further at a later time
